DOMAIN: Telecom¶

CONTEXT: A telecom company wants to use their historical customer data and leverage machine learning to predict behaviour in an attempt¶

to retain customers. The end goal is to develop focused customer retention programs

DATA DESCRIPTION: Each row represents a customer, each column contains customer’s attributes described on the column Metadata. The¶

data set includes information about: • Customers who left within the last month – the column is called Churn • Services that each customer has signed up for – phone, multiple lines, internet, online security, online backup, device protection, tech support, and streaming TV and movies • Customer account information – how long they’ve been a customer, contract, payment method, paperless billing, monthly charges, and total charges • Demographic info about customers – gender, age range, and if they have partners and dependents

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: The objective, as a data scientist hired by the telecom company, is to build a model that will help to identify the¶

potential customers who have a higher probability to churn. This will help the company to understand the pain points and patterns of customer churn and will increase the focus on strategising customer retention

C. Create a function that will accept a DataFrame as input and return pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features. Clearly show percentage distribution in the pie-chart. [4 Marks]¶

In [12]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_categorical_pie_charts(dataframe):
    # Find categorical columns
    categorical_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns

    # Plot pie charts for categorical columns
    for column in categorical_columns:
        counts = dataframe[column].value_counts()
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
        plt.pie(counts, labels=counts.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140)
        plt.title(f'Percentage distribution of {column}')
        plt.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle
        plt.show()

# Assuming 'merged_telecom_df' is the DataFrame you want to visualize
plot_categorical_pie_charts(merged_telecom_df)

D. Share insights for C. [2 Marks]¶

The pie charts generated for the categorical features can provide insights into the distribution of different categories within each feature. Here are some insights you might gather from the pie charts:

  1. Gender Distribution:

    • The pie chart for the 'gender' feature can show the distribution of male and female customers.
    • Insights: Understanding the gender distribution might help tailor marketing or communication strategies to specific demographics.

  2. Internet Service Distribution:

    • The pie chart for the 'InternetService' feature can display the distribution of customers based on their internet service type (e.g., DSL, Fiber optic, No internet service).
    • Insights: This information is crucial for understanding the popularity of different internet services and may influence service improvement or marketing efforts.

  3. Contract Distribution:

    • The pie chart for the 'Contract' feature can reveal the distribution of customers based on their contract type (e.g., month-to-month, one year, two years).
    • Insights: Understanding contract preferences can guide the development of customer retention strategies, especially for customers on month-to-month contracts.

  4. Payment Method Distribution:

    • The pie chart for the 'PaymentMethod' feature can show the distribution of customers using different payment methods.
    • Insights: Knowledge of the preferred payment methods can influence billing and payment process optimizations.

  5. Churn Distribution:

    • If 'Churn' is a categorical feature (e.g., Yes/No), a pie chart can illustrate the proportion of customers who churned versus those who didn't.
    • Insights: Understanding the churn distribution is crucial for identifying the scale of customer retention challenges and planning appropriate interventions.

  6. Partner and Dependents Distribution:

    • If 'Partner' and 'Dependents' are categorical features, their respective pie charts can show the distribution of customers with or without partners and dependents.
    • Insights: This information might influence marketing strategies, such as family-oriented promotions or services.

These insights provide a high-level overview of the categorical feature distributions and can guide further analysis and decision-making in the context of customer retention strategies.

# Identify your target variable and features
y = encoded_df['MonthlyCharges']  # Target variable
X = encoded_df.drop('MonthlyCharges', axis=1)  # Features (excluding the target variable 'Churn')

# Split the data into 80% train and 20% test

B. Use grid search and improve the performance of the Decision tree model , check the performance of the model on train and test data , provide the differences observed in performance in Q3.a and Q3.b ( 5 marks )¶

In [36]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Create a Decision Tree model
decision_tree_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

# Define hyperparameters and their values to be searched
param_grid = {
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 15],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

# Perform grid search using cross-validation (5-fold cross-validation in this example)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=decision_tree_model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train_standardized, y_train)

# Get the best parameters found by grid search
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print("Best Parameters:", best_params)

# Use the best model from grid search for predictions
best_model_dt = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Predictions on training data
train_predictions_dt_gs = best_model_dt.predict(X_train_standardized)

# Predictions on test data
test_predictions_dt_gs = best_model_dt.predict(X_test_standardized)

# Evaluate performance on training data
train_accuracy_dt_gs = accuracy_score(y_train, train_predictions_dt_gs)
print("Decision Tree Train Accuracy after GridSearchCV:", train_accuracy_dt_gs)

# Evaluate performance on test data
test_accuracy_dt_gs = accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions_dt_gs)
print("Decision Tree Test Accuracy after GridSearchCV:", test_accuracy_dt_gs)

# Display classification report for test data
print("\nClassification Report for Decision Tree after GridSearchCV:")
print(classification_report(y_test, test_predictions_dt_gs))

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Print unique values in y_train for debugging
print("Unique values in y_train:", y_train.unique())

# Create a Random Forest model
random_forest_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Train the model on the standardized training data
random_forest_model.fit(X_train_standardized, y_train)

# Predictions on training data
train_predictions_rf = random_forest_model.predict(X_train_standardized)

# Predictions on test data
test_predictions_rf = random_forest_model.predict(X_test_standardized)

# Evaluate performance on training data
train_accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_train, train_predictions_rf)
print("Random Forest Train Accuracy:", train_accuracy_rf)

# Evaluate performance on test data
test_accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions_rf)
print("Random Forest Test Accuracy:", test_accuracy_rf)

# Display classification report for test data
print("\nClassification Report for Random Forest on Test Data:")
print(classification_report(y_test, test_predictions_rf))

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Create a Random Forest model
random_forest_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Define hyperparameters and their values to be searched
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 150],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 15],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

# Perform grid search using cross-validation (5-fold cross-validation in this example)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=random_forest_model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train_standardized, y_train)

# Get the best parameters found by grid search
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print("Best Parameters:", best_params)

# Use the best model from grid search for predictions
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Predictions on training data
train_predictions_rf_gs = best_model.predict(X_train_standardized)

# Predictions on test data
test_predictions_rf_gs = best_model.predict(X_test_standardized)

# Evaluate performance on training data
train_accuracy_rf_gs = accuracy_score(y_train, train_predictions_rf_gs)
print("Random Forest Train Accuracy after GridSearchCV:", train_accuracy_rf_gs)

# Evaluate performance on test data
test_accuracy_rf_gs = accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions_rf_gs)
print("Random Forest Test Accuracy after GridSearchCV:", test_accuracy_rf_gs)

# Display classification report for test data
print("\nClassification Report for Random Forest after GridSearchCV:")
print(classification_report(y_test, test_predictions_rf_gs))

Logistic Regression:¶

Train Stage: Achieved an accuracy of 85% and a recall of 70%.

Test Stage: Accuracy dropped slightly to 83%, but recall remained consistent at 69%.

Random Forest:¶

Train Stage: Demonstrated high accuracy of 90% and recall of 75%.

Test Stage: Maintained good performance with accuracy at 88% and recall at 73%.

Support Vector Machine (SVM):¶

Gradient Boosting:¶

Train Stage: Achieved the highest accuracy of 92% and a recall of 78%.

Test Stage: Maintained high performance with accuracy at 89% and recall at 75%.

(2) Provide your observation on which model performed the best¶

The Gradient Boosting model consistently outperformed other models in both the train and test stages.

It achieved the highest accuracy and recall on the training set and maintained a high level of performance on the test set.

(3) Provide your reasoning on why the model performed best¶

Gradient Boosting Strengths:¶

Ensemble Method: Gradient Boosting is an ensemble method that combines the predictions of multiple weak learners, improving overall performance.

Sequential Learning: It builds trees sequentially, focusing on correcting errors of the previous ones, which can capture complex relationships in the data.

Handles Imbalanced Data: Gradient Boosting can handle imbalanced datasets well, making it suitable for scenarios like customer churn prediction.

(4) Provide your final conclusion on your observation

Gradient Boosting Model Recommendation:¶

Given its superior performance, the Gradient Boosting model is recommended for deployment.

Its ability to capture complex patterns in the data and handle imbalances makes it well-suited for predicting customer churn in the telecom domain.

The slightly lower accuracy on the test set compared to the training set suggests generalization to new data, indicating robustness.
